The overarching goal of this workshop was to form active working groups with the following main objectives:

Learn recent research trends and useful techniques in operator theory;
Discuss strategies and solve open problems in operator theory and related areas;
Initiate solid and long lasting research collaborations among participants;
Increase the number of female researchers in operator theory and related areas; and
Create an active network of support for female researchers and junior researchers in operator theory and related areas.


Due to the pandemic, the originally planned conference in Summer 2020 was postponed and instead an initial virtual meeting was organized at the Lorentz Center, July 26-July 30, 2021. We were finally able to host our in-person gathering at the University of Memphis, October 13-20, 2022. At the virtual meeting, we had several introdcutory lectures for all participants to learn about recent research trends and techniques in operator theory and we successfully formed five working groups that met frequently throughout that week to pursue collaborative projects. At the in-person meeting, several participants from various working groups attended. Participants gave talks about their recent work and open questions they were seeking collaboration on. Several working groups have continued self-organizing ongoing group meetings throughout the year and at least one new working group was formed at the in-person meeting in October 2022. At least one working groups has published a paper as a result of their collaboration, and at least two other working groups have papers in preparation at the time of writing this report.

While our virtual and in-person workshops have accomplished the major goals of our project as outlined above, we continue to strive to build and maintain a community for female researchers and junior researchers where ideas are comfortably exchanged and collaborations flourish. Many of the working groups have continued supporting our network for researchers in operator theory through weekly group meetings and inviting them to give talks at conferences, meetings, and colloquia. Furthermore, we have continued to grow the number of young researchers in operator theory by welcoming additional graduate students and international participants.

